13 Design Decisions
BEFORE

Collections separate from All Items
Prevents archive collapse and keeps intentional organization separate from passive saving

Link paste as primary input
Reduces input friction and speeds up item capture by matching existing behavior

Preview then Add for first-time capture
Removes save ambiguity and separates intake from organization

Recently Added as Home entry point
Keeps recent activity visible and helps users track what they’ve added

Onboarding generates starter items
Solves the cold start problem so users can try outfits immediately

DURING

Structured outfit logic (tops, bottoms, accessories)
Reduces choice overload while keeping outputs coherent

Smart pairing suggestions
Shows relevant combinations at the right moment and increases cart value

Show only generated outfit on canvas
Keeps focus on the output and reduces visual clutter during evaluation

Save, Share, Regenerate actions post-generation
Supports key actions after generation without forcing immediate decisions

AFTER

To Buy as purchase layer
Groups items for checkout and captures purchase intent

Items used with direct purchase actions
Connects generated outfits directly to buying without extra steps

Keep all generated outfits reviewable
Lets users revisit past outputs without losing options

Alerts for price and stock changes
Brings users back when items become available or cheaper

SYSTEM

Add vs All Items vs Collections vs Save Outfit
Uses clear actions to separate capture, storage, and saving results

Outfits reference items — no duplication
Keeps items reusable and avoids inconsistent data

Collections are not the archive
Keeps organization intentional instead of mixing it with storage

Defer model setup to first Try-On
Avoids early friction by asking for photos only when needed